<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-05-22T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-05-22T21:00:00-05:00" n="153" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d153">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7913: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-05-23T11:00:00+09:00">May 23, 1936—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 23—2:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>111. According to the best information available to the Military Attaché,
                            the Japanese Garrison in North China will be increased to <pb facs="0262" n="167" xml:id="pg_167"/> about 4300 officers and men,
                            or to 4675 if additional field artillery is to be sent. Japanese
                            officers here deny that an army division is to be organized in North
                            China.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>